segments.text: 1982, this is Terry Anderson.
We are interviewing General Kennedy.
You were born May 16, 1904, in Leggett, Texas.
Let's start out by talking a little bit about your background.
Could you tell me about your parents?
Both my parents were born in Texas.
Only one of my grandparents came in about the time of the Civil War, just after the Civil War.
I grew up between Polk County, Texas and Jefferson County, Texas.
Polk County at that time was the big thicket, in other words, the country background.
I went away to sea when I was 16 and went to Europe and up east and to South America and Mexico.
No kidding, why?
Oh, I thought it would be an adventure.
Did your family have the money to send you off to?
No, I worked on trapped ships.
Oh, you did?
Yeah, and came back and finished high school and then went on to M.M.
from there.
And so, now why did you decide to leave when you were 16 years old?
Most people don't leave home at that age.
Frankly, I don't think this is too pertinent to what you have in mind, but since you asked the question, I'll answer it.

Owing to an illness in my family in Beaumont, I spent a year in high school in Galveston living with my aunt and working in the afternoons, but spending my spare time between the gymnasium and the library in YMCA.
I read Jack London's books and got the idea of adventure.
Now, mind you, there's a lesson for youngsters in this.
It doesn't belong in your tape.
It sure does.
We want to know about it.
I worked by, which means in the harbor, on the ship, Messboy, until we sailed.
And we took on the crew, a good deal of it, just before sailing.
Well, the night that we were first at sea, a man tried to kill me.
I mean, serious matter.
He chased me with a fire axe, and as it happened, a man saw him and just cold cocked him as we turned the corner.
And they put the man in irons, of course.
It turns out he was a drug addict.
And they kept him in the pokey until we got to Norfolk.
But as I lay in my bunk that night, I said to myself,
This is adventure, and I don't like it.
It was a little bit too much adventure.
Yes, exactly.
And that is how I happen now.
What did your parents think of you leaving home at sixteen?
My father actually came down to the ship to see me off.
talked to a large brother of his that he'd turned up on the ship about me, but my parents didn't tell me what not to do.
If I did something which was patently wrong, they made it clear to me and punished me for it, but they didn't, see, for example, my wife thought for a long time that I ran away to sea.
I didn't run away to sea at all.
I just went, that's all.
I wasn't running away from anything.
As it happened, you see, on that first ship, I expected to come back and go back to high school in the fall.
But it turned out we broke down, and that was another unpleasant adventure.
Nevertheless, when I got back into the East Coast, it was too late to go back to school, so I just caught another ship and went to South America.
upshot of all this, I came back and finished high school.
But as you might suspect, that left me in a relatively peculiar position with my peers because back then, people from East Texas, hell, some of them never left the county.
Let's go elsewhere.
And I had some experiences which were different.
Anyway, I don't know that that makes any, I don't think it has any bearing on what we're talking about.
I want to know about the background of each former student who became a general, and that's why I'm asking you these questions.
All right, then I'll proceed.
I worked my way through A&M.
Before we get to A&M, I'd like to know a little bit about this cruise.
Now when you went to South America and when you went to Europe, what did you learn?
What kind of impact did that have on you?
Oh, I think it's obvious enough.
You learn that people are different.
You learn that just because people live a certain way and think a certain way down in Polk County,
You know that from your own travels.
And a certain, I should say, a certain, call it cynicism?
I don't know what you'd call it.
You've seen men get killed.
Yeah.
And that makes a difference.
You know the reasons for it and that sort of thing.
Mm-hm.
Can you tell me a little bit about your mother and your father?
My mother died when I was young and I just barely in the vaguest way remember her.
She was the daughter of a physician who, like my other grandfather, was embittered by the Civil War and came back, came from where he was down
to Texas and finished up in that small town.
It isn't even there anymore.
Anyway, she died and that was partially the reason why I spent my summers with my grandmother, her mother, who lived up there, far back in the country.
My stepmother was a wonderfully good woman and couldn't have been a better mother to me.
My father

at the time I suppose we were talking about, was he sold oil well supplies and helped set up a business in Beaumont, Texas that, oh hell, in recent years they just sold out of interest in it that he'd aired to us.
But his background was this, his father
was a Presbyterian minister, embittered by the Civil War, and came in, old Indianola, which was later washed away.
But my mother, I mean my grandmother, who had come down in a wagon train from Virginia just before the Civil War, and all the men went back, you see.
Anyway, they married, and my father was born in Cthulhu.
when it was nothing, not much, still isn't.
Now, this might bear on it, I don't know, but my grandfather and grandmother were absolutely intent that he should get an education and were reasonably sure he couldn't get it in Texas.
So they sent him to a prep school in Tennessee, an old prep school,
And then on to University of Virginia, where he was kicked out for ungentlemanly conduct.
A man called him a damn Texas Longhorn.
He knocked him off the upstairs porch for that.
And then he found out that my grandparents had been literally starving themselves to ensure his education.
By that time, my grandfather was the chaplain.
of the prison at Huntsville.
My father finished his degree at Huntsville.
The college is still there as a matter of fact.
And then he taught school down in that big thicket place where he met my mother and went through some permutations and ended up as a businessman and had a pretty good one.
I say a pretty good one, he was a real good one.
He loved people and
was a natural extrovert and a good athlete.
Things that I know was.
But he, I think, enjoyed his life.
Now, what led into that was you're asking me whether they had objected in any way.
It never occurred to me that they would object.
It was generally conceded this was my business.
And I think that's right.
So your father then wasn't the domineering type father or the authoritarian type?
No, he was very, very explicit.
When there was something I couldn't do, by God, I knew it.
The only athletic activity I ever engaged in was boxing.
And I did that because, hell, I had a set of boxing gloves from the time I could walk, I guess.
In any case, after I came back,
from the sea.
I boxed at the YMCA there in Beaumont, and at that time Beaumont was a hell-bent sports town.
And a fellow classmate of mine, they had some pretty good boxers, and I worked out with them too.
And I got it in my head that I would be a, you know, a preliminary.
You get ten bucks, man, that's a hell of a lot of money.
But he said, you absolutely won't do that.
And that was it.
In retrospect, he knew exactly what he was talking about.
I didn't.
But it was no question in my mind.
Since he said I couldn't do it, I couldn't do it.
That was the way he was.
But those things which were my decisions, he let me make them and let them die by them, too.
Did he want you to further your education?
He was very interested in it.
But you see, he kept in the background some of what he and my grandmother, the one, his mother, thought about me, and thought about, for example, this business of mine going to sea.
I didn't even know until my father died, and I was clearing up his affairs, and he had saved the letters that they had exchanged.
It was in the night.
And I'd sat there quiet because I didn't know that they felt as deeply about this as they did.
Well, that's good.
They looked at it as my decision, but they absolutely deplored it, of course.
But I didn't know that.
Yeah.
But I don't think this is important.
Now, let's talk about your education.
Oh, well.
I want to talk, before we get to Texas A&M, can you tell me a little bit about your education in high school about that time?
Well, gosh, let's see if I can think of anything very consequential.
Well, where'd you go to high school?
I finished high school in Vermont.
Okay, okay.
What were your favorite topics?
What kind of classes did you like?
Well, I suppose I'll have a confession to make on that.
I looked on high school as something that you got through.
And I carried this over to A&M to a degree.
What the object is, find out what the teacher wants and give it to them.
That's the way you make good grades.
That's what the thing's all about.
Education is something you do yourself.
The teacher is a person who, if you're lucky, will help you do it.
But that's neither here nor there.
The object in the teacher-scholar relationship for me in high school was find out what they want and let them have it.
In other words, those interests that I had were not too much related to school.
So in other words, you didn't really care much for school.
No, the system at A&M was so much more disciplined, so much more demanding, you couldn't get away with that.
Oh, I see.
I made good grades because I still played that tune, but you had to do the work.
In high school, if that was true, I didn't know it, I didn't feel it.
Oh, hell, I don't think there's anything that...
If there is, I can't remember.
Oh, shoot.
No, I can't think of anything.
Okay, let's then talk about your favorite.
Let's talk about going to A&M.
Why did you decide on A&M?
Frankly, because of the money.
And also because when I finished high school, I wrote to MIT and Caltech.
I knew I wanted to be an engineer.
Because I figured out, look, I had dug ditches for a living.
And by that time, and I knew damn well there was a better way to make a living.
So MIT came back and said they didn't really think that I probably could qualify.
California didn't even answer.
And by that time, I knew what the
what the financial aspects of this were, and that's why I went there now.
I knew it was a good engineering school, and I'm sure it still is.
So you had made up your mind that you wanted to be an engineer?
Oh yes, yes.
Look, for example, let me, this is Picayune, I think, but in the process of working in the engine room of ships,
I found out what you had to do to qualify to be an engineer on a ship.
But if you came out of an engineering school with B.S.
in engineering, Jesus Christ, you could work three months, pass the test, and be one.
But it took you years and years of working in the engine room before you could even take the examination.
That's why it made sense to me to go get an engineering degree
But you see, I worked on construction jobs.
That's the way I made my expenses at A&M.
I was lucky.
I made enough in the summers to pay my way.
Not with any leftover, I might add.
I worked at A&M.
What type of jobs did you do at A&M, the construction work?
Well, no, there wasn't any.
No, what you'd call fallout for work, and it was two bits an hour, it didn't make a difference what you did.
The first few years I worked mostly cutting grass, trimming grass, whatever.
And then somebody found out that I knew how to weld, so I signed on at the shops in ag engineering.
I didn't do much work, to tell you the truth, because there wasn't much work to do, but it was still 25 cents an hour.
It didn't make any difference what you did.
But this was for pocket money.
I made enough, fortunately, in the summers to carry my other expenses.
Did your father help pay for tuition?
No, he didn't.
Not that I didn't ask him to.
I think he probably would have if I'd asked him to, but I didn't want to ask him to.
My last year, since I had many other things to do other than just what I had been doing, I borrowed a couple hundred dollars from my aunt.
Maidenhead, the one that my father's sister, who I'd gone to school with, lived with in Galveston.
We were close.
But prior to that time, I'd made enough to cover.
I don't think any of this is too germane, but if you wanted to What aboutcan you tell me about your core outfit?
went through an artillery.
Now this I think is pertinent, and this I think can possibly make a contribution.
The ROTC system that I went through with was extremely beneficial to my experience in the military, very much so.
I want to distinguish between the
OTC living system and the MS&T, what you were taught in the lectures in the department, they were valueless.
Quite without value.
The military science, you mean?
Military science and tactics was quite without value.
I'm not under any illusion about that.
It had no educational content.
It was something you did because you had to.
And something the tactical officers did because they had to.
But the ROT system that I lived in was something else.
This taught, for example, first thing you have to do is learn how to do as you're told, to take orders.
Sure.
Then as you gradually
acquire authority, you also acquire the responsibility that goes with it.
Now, this is a must in all forms of the military, obviously, but frequently it takes a long, long time for man to learn that.
The ROTC system that I went through compressed that and taught it to you in four years.
It also taught you that the essence of a military operation, I don't care what it is, infantry, cavalry, air force, is to get a group of men to do a thing, to attain a common goal.
But, and this is very important, it taught you that that group of men was made up of individuals, each of whom
was different.
There are no such thing as clones in human beings except the twin.
There are not many of those.
This is what the ROTC system that I went through taught me.
Now, this was not a common of all ROTC systems.
Although the military academy system was superior in many ways, it was not common to that system.
Okay, would you like to compare the Texas A&M system to the academy system, the West Point system?
I can't do that for now because I don't even know what the system is.
Back then, I mean... Oh, back then, yes, of course.
As I said, the multi-academy system was superior in some ways.
But in the simple way that I'm talking about, it was not.
It took the military academy graduate much longer to acquire the things which the Texas A&M graduate had to acquire by living in it.
But I want to make this plain.
that in later years, when you're in the business of selecting people you know absolutely nothing about, and you have no other way to go, you'll take the military academy graduate.
Why?
Because he's been through something that is pretty goddamn tough.
You know that much about him.
He may be an utter bust, but you know that much about him.
So that's why
They do stand out in the military, and why?
Frequently they get plus jobs because they should.
But the system that I am admiring, and the old system, and I don't even know whether it still pertains to Texas A&M.
I'm talking about what I know.
I know it did not pertain in, for example, it does not pertain, for example, in the University of Texas ROTC system.
It is not there, and there's no use talking about it.
It isn't.
The OTC system at the University of Texas that I observed when I was up there after retirement is totally different.
Maybe it has some merits, but I've not had the one I'm talking about.
I'm not saying that the Texas A&M College, now the university, is the ideal system.
It isn't.
I think it's proper to enter a criticism of it, since I have it complimented so highly, at least I think I have.
This is not a criticism of the institution.
There's not a criticism of the faculty when I'm about to voice.
This is the style of the student body at the time I attended.
Mind you,
It was quite homogeneous then.
The style of the student body probably was the genesis of the Aggie joke.
The Aggie joke didn't exist when I was there, but it does now.
It was to use vulgarisms, cliches, bad grammar, and be proud of it.
This was a handicap.
It was a handicap with a number of engineers, at least, who got out of it and didn't know they had.
It did not handicap them in the preliminary work of, say, a bull gang to build a bridge or something of that sort.
But when it came time to explain a more complex project, it was a handicap.
was, in my opinion, the criticism of the institution at the time I went there, but not the institution as such.
It was a student body.
And if you want me to explain it, I can't.
I'm just saying it existed.
This, for example, in later years, you have to put people in place to do things.
If you have a job,

you don't have enough material, you don't have enough people, you don't have enough money, you're going to put a Texas A&M man, a youngster in charge of it, Georgia Tech, Iowa, an old land grant school guy, you don't put MIT, Yale, Stanford, because they're not good at that kind of thing.
when they come right out.
On the other hand, if you have a complex project to put out on paper, to lay it out in a persuasive way, you don't put that A&M man on it.
You do put the other guy on it.
Am I making myself clear?
I'm trying to explain this particular handicap.
I think when you compliment something, you ought to balance it.
That's what I'm trying to do.
Now, let's proceed.
I didn't enter the service by intent.
I was going to South America to build beautiful power plants.
I knew what I wanted to do, and I knew how to go about it.
You wanted to be an engineer first.
Yes, of course, and a construction engineer.
Because it is good work.
But I'd worked in construction camps enough to know that it's good work, and it pays well.
But when you work so, you don't have anybody to talk to.
All right.
I was walking back home from work.
back from the mess hall one evening with another cop of a mechanical engineering graduate in the early spring, late summer, late winter, talking about what we were going to do after we finished.
And he said he was going to the flying school.
And I said, what flying school?
And he told me, and it turns out they're running a flying school for free.
down here in San Antonio.
Well, I didn't know that.
And, you know, it's hard to get around in South America.
And I thought it would be pretty handy to learn how to fly.
And so I checked into it and went to the flying school.
Now, I liked the people.
I liked to fly the airplanes.
But more than anything else, it was something
The people I enjoyed being with, and I don't regret it in any sense of the word, but I don't want to convey the idea that I went through the ROTC system at A&M with the idea of going in the military.
I didn't at all.
This was a happenstance.
And I've enjoyed my service career.
It fit what I like to do.
But you didn't plan on this.
You didn't plan on a military career.
No, I didn't.
I took the commission because it was available.
When I finished the flying school, I knew I liked it.
I liked the people I was with.
Hell, some of my best friends, the classmates from flying school, and the only long, old-time friends I guess I've got.
People that, I don't know, shared a common interest.
It was fun.
And that's how I got involved in the military.
Can you tell me a little bit about the flying school?
What type?
It was down in San Antone, and you graduated there in 1929.
What type of airplanes were you trained in?
Well, at Brooks, Brooks was two sections, primary and basic.
Yeah.
And the advanced school was at Kelly.
Yeah.
And primary, we had a primary trainer, and basic we had a DH-4, a DH airplane, and at Kelly we had an old-fashioned B-4 and B-5 bomber.
Those don't mean anything nowadays.
They're sticking wire airplanes, all of them.
The school was, of course, run to provide the Air Corps with pilots.
Yes.
But it also provided the airlines with pilots.
You didn't have to come into the service, you see.
Really?
No.
You were offered the chance if you wanted to.
You did take a reserve commission.
I already had one in the artillery, but
I just transferred to the Air Corps.
And since the regular commission was offered to graduates, college graduates, without examination, I just took it.
See, I figured at the time I'd spend maybe another year flying airplanes to get that much more experience before I went on to South America.
It turned out, as I said, I liked the people, I liked the work, I liked the airplanes, and stayed in.
Simple.
So once you graduated from flight school, then you decided not to go down to South America.
You decided to stay...
I still was, you might say I was ambivalent about it at the time.
I finished flight school.
I would say
In retrospect, yes, I still intended to do that.
But I thought that this much more flying experience would be helpful.
It wasn't a bad decision because the flight school taught you to fly all right, no doubt of that.
And all my classmates didn't come under the service, not at all.
One, for example, an old friend up at San Angelo is a geophysicist.
And he'd been around the world a good deal, too, working on various geophysical operations.
And the exploration chief that he was associated with tried to get him to leave the flying school to come take over a job in Venezuela, for example.
And at the time, I remember it so well, we were on DHs, and it was the time when the
incomers were being washed out meeting the board.
Well, he went to meet the board to get out to go do this thing along with these guys who were meeting the board who didn't want to get out.
Well, he came back looking kind of funny and I asked him and he said, no, they're not going to let me out.
Well, that suited him right down to the ground because he did want to go on through the flying school.
He liked it.
And it gave him an out with the guy that was trying to get him anyway when he
When flying school was over, he did leave and went on down to South America and did a job and came back and did something here and so forth.
That was the kind of thing.
Now, when the war came, of course, he came back, got in uniform.
Sure.
In fact, he and I worked together for a while.
But before we get too far ahead, I'd like you to talk a little bit about some of the things about the Corps cadets.
What did you think about the hazing?
Look,
I told you that I'd been around the world a good deal.
I don't know a good gentlemanly word to express what I thought about it.
Nevertheless, I was kicked out one year for that.
You were?
This is a long story, and I'll shorten it up.
It turned out that the youngster who made a case against me didn't get his facts straight.
So when I met the board, the disciplinary board at NN, I didn't have to lie.
I didn't have to because they didn't ask me the right questions.
Nevertheless, they knew I was guilty of something, and I was.
And so President was then Bazell, and when they eliminated me, this was a part and parcel of a pretty big uproar at the time.
A whole goddamn troop of cavalrymen got kicked out at the same time I was in the artillery, as I told you.
And I and one other from the artillery was kicked out.
Anyway, Bazell called me in and asked me if I wanted to go up to what was then a part of A&M, Arlington, a two-year college at the time.
Anyway, I went up there and finished out the year.
This delayed me graduating from A&M, but on the other hand, gave me a chance to take some courses I wanted to take that weren't in the normal curriculum.
To get back to your question, I can't express it in, I was contemptuous of it, let's put it that way.
It is a piss poor way to run a railroad.
It perpetuated the puerility and young men are all too prone to that anyhow, so I don't want to say any more about it.
Okay, okay.
It was a go-ahead.
What did you like and what did you dislike about being in the Corps?
You know, I never gave that any thought.
I still haven't, apparently, because I don't seem to be able to answer your question.
This is a thing you did.
You did it in order to reach your goal.
I didn't think about whether I liked it or disliked it.
Wait a minute.
I can say what I liked about it.
At the time, I went through
We were horse drawn artillery.
And we could go to the stables over the weekend and get a horse and ride in the countryside, free his hair.
That was great.
My roommate, my last year roommate, was a member of the pistol team.
And we could go.
Of course, he had a pistol that he shot with that was different.
And draw ammunition.
and go out in the country and shoot targets, or rabbits, if we wanted to.
The work, the academic work, with a few exceptions, was a challenge.
And I personally like challenges.
I like that.
To ask me what I didn't like about it, oh,
Howard Soldier.
That style, I didn't like that.
There was no way to say you didn't like it or act as though you didn't like it.
But I want to be clear about this.
My English prof, one year assigned and one I managed to get into his class, was an Oxford graduate.
with Laurels in English, there was nothing wrong with the faculty.
There was nothing the faculty could do about this.
I didn't like that.
I liked being a battery commander in my senior year.
It was a responsible job, and any responsible job is a gratifying job.
I don't mean by that that I think I was popular.
I don't think I was.
In fact, I think I was probably pretty generally disliked because I was different.
And goddammit, I had to be.
I was older.
As you can tell from my age when I graduated, I was older than my contemporaries and hadn't been around more.
Much of what they were interested in, I thought, was pretty childish.
I don't want to say any more about this because I'm afraid I'm sounding too critical.
Well, I have another question.
You became general officer.
In what way do you think A&M or the Corps of Cadets helped you in becoming a position of that responsibility?
I have to be explicit.
And in the way I told you about, in the understanding that there are no duplicates in human beings, we're dealing with equipment which has to be duplicate.
Every part has to be the same.
It allowed me to avoid the common misunderstanding in the military that men are that way too.
They're not.
A&M helped me with that, in fact, probably taught me this, but certainly much more than I learned in the construction business, for example.
I think I learned that at A&M, and I think it was very helpful.
Also, in the early years of your service, engineering is
is probably the best type of education, academic.
That's why the academies are basically engineering schools.
As time goes on, that is no longer true.
Technology is a given.
You have to understand it, but you don't have to deal with it intimately.
In my observation,
There comes a time in your service when perhaps you might have been better trained in law.
Later on, there's a time when perhaps you might have been better trained in, say, international relationships.
There's never a time when history is inappropriate.
History must, because it is the explanation
of forces which you must deal with in your later years.
In fact, in your years as a general officer.
But those things which a general officer most often is required to deal with, you don't learn in school.
Let me talk about two men who are on your list who I think exemplify the
qualities that I am going to try to describe.
One of them is Al Ludeke.
Do you know him?
Yes, I've interviewed him.
He's in and out of A&M.
Al is a very talented man.
He has proved it in many pursuits.
The other one is Bernie Schriever, who's in Washington.
Now, both these men have something that I don't have, so I can
I can single them out better to illustrate what I'm talking about.
There comes a time when you're required to solve problems to oversimplify the political and the administrative function.
You solve them
by reason of knowing what this force wants and this force wants and what this force wants and what you might approximate to get the job done that goddammit you ought to get done.
Now, you don't learn this in school.
Neither, I mean, both Al and Bernie are good engineers, but that isn't what caused them to be successful.
It's this quality that I don't believe I can describe to you, that both of them had, and if you haven't already, you will talk to them, this ability.
Now, I want to point out that just the background and the quality doesn't ensure success.
I want to point out the obvious that so many men overlook.
The quality of luck.
The business of time and place and luck.
You can't overlook that.
Hell, I know lots of better men than I am.
I never got to be generals.
Some of them, unfortunately, blame themselves for it, and they couldn't be wronger.
And you might keep that in mind for yourself.
I don't give a damn what you're doing.
Luck is going to enter into it.
Which one is more important, the individual's own characteristics and training or luck?
Oh, obviously it's characteristics because you can't do anything about luck.
I think that's pretty obvious.

Okay, well let's go back now to, you graduated from flying school, you became a second lieutenant in the Army Air Corps in 1929, and then your first duty station, was that at the Air Corps Technical School?
Oh no, no, Dodd Field, right across the way.
Okay.
And Dodd and Book's Field, observation.
And what were you doing there?
normal second lieutenant duties.
I was assistant operations and assistant engineering and that sort of thing.
I had to do other, back then you did everything.
But your primary duties were, I guess, operations and engineering.
And how long were you there?
Oh, I was at Dodd, I guess about a year.
And then went to Chanute and came back
Wait a minute, we moved to Brooks.
We formed a group at Brooks.
Brooks changed the flag.
